The following is an episode list for the [Nickelodeon](/wiki/Nickelodeon
"Nickelodeon") [animated television series](/wiki/Animated_television_series
"Animated television series") _[My Life as a Teenage
Robot](/wiki/My_Life_as_a_Teenage_Robot "My Life as a Teenage Robot")_. The
show officially began on Nickelodeon in the United States on August 1, 2003
and, after the second season, new episodes ended on that channel in 2005.
Eventually, the show got picked up for a third season that aired on [Nicktoons
Network](/wiki/Nicktoons_\(TV_channel\) "Nicktoons \(TV channel\)") in the
United States from 2008 to 2009. The series ended on May 2, 2009, with all 40
episodes aired.

### Season 1
(2003–04)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_My_Life_as_a_Teenage_Robot_episodes&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Season 1 \(2003–04\)")]

_My Life as a Teenage Robot_ season 1 episodes No. in  
series | No. in  
season | Title | Directed by | Storyboard by | Original air date[4]  
---|---|---|---|---|---  
1 | 1a | "It Came From Next Door" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Alex Kirwan & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | August 1, 2003 (2003-08-01)  
Jenny makes her first contact with the outside world, meeting Brad and Tuck
Carbuckle for the first time. While Brad immediately accepts Jenny as a new
friend, Tuck does not quite see her as anything other than a "evil robot
cyborg".  
2 | 1b | "Pest Control" | Tim Walker & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chris Mitchell | August 1, 2003 (2003-08-01)  
Having vowed revenge on her for all the injustices placed upon them, Dr.
Wakeman's mutant lab rats, led by the evil genius Vladimir, plan to destroy
her by taking control of Jenny's body.  
3 | 2a | "Raggedy Android" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Alex Kirwan & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | August 8, 2003 (2003-08-08)  
Jenny wants to go to the town fair, but Dr. Wakeman fears that Jenny will
spook the townspeople with her presence. When Jenny gets a hold of a prototype
"exo-skin" for her to wear, she sees her chance to mingle with the fairgoers;
unfortunately, its mangled appearance only scares them. Meanwhile, Tuck
attempts to conquer his fear of Ferris wheels.  
4 | 2b | "Class Action" | Tim Walker & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | August 8, 2003 (2003-08-08)  
On her first day of high school, Jenny seeks to make some new friends, and she
thinks she can find some in the arrogant Brit and Tiff Crust. Unfortunately,
the Crust cousins do not share the same feelings and plan to humiliate her.  
5 | 3a | "Attack of The 5½ Ft. Geek" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Ashley Lenz | August 15, 2003 (2003-08-15)  
When Jenny saves local school geek Sheldon from a gang of bullies, he quickly
becomes smitten with her and does not want to leave her alone.  
6 | 3b | "Doom With A View" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | August 15, 2003 (2003-08-15)  
A simple snowball battle between Jenny, Brad, and Tuck is interrupted by a
strange robot ambassador who wants to make Jenny the newest member of the
Cluster, a legion of robots headquartered on the planet Cluster Prime that
plans to enslave humans for manual labor. When she refuses, the ambassador
commences war against her.  
7 | 4a | "Ear No Evil" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Mary Hanley | August 22, 2003 (2003-08-22)  
Jenny wants to get ear piercings, but her mother refuses to give her ears.
Sheldon offers to step in and help, but the ears he builds end up being
disproportionately large on Jenny's head.  
8 | 4b | "Unlicensed Flying Object" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | August 22, 2003 (2003-08-22)  
Brad is disappointed by his lack of a driver's license, and Jenny's attempts
to help him. Soon, he takes up joyriding in abandoned UFOs as a new hobby.  
9 | 5a | "Party Machine" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Carlos Ramos | September 5, 2003 (2003-09-05)  
Jenny and Brad's secret party is a hit, but between keeping the party-goers
under control, keeping the house in one piece, and keeping a group of tiny
multiplying aliens from invading Earth, Jenny has her hands full.  
10 | 5b | "Speak No Evil" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chris Mitchell & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | September 5, 2003 (2003-09-05)  
While on a mission in Japan, Jenny winds up losing one of her language system
discs for English speech. Unable to switch off from speaking in full Japanese,
she encounters problems in speaking to people. She uses this to her advantage,
however, to make peace with a Japanese creature that grows with and is hurt by
water.  
11 | 6a | "See No Evil" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chuck Klein | September 12, 2003 (2003-09-12)  
Dr. Wakeman is proud of her newest enhancement for Jenny: multi-functional
eyes that can see anything in any view. Jenny likes them until she sees how
they look on her. She refuses to use them and fumbles around town without any
sight until she finally realizes she needs them to fight an invisible villain.  
12 | 6b | "The Great Unwashed" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Bernie Petterson | September 12, 2003 (2003-09-12)  
Jenny has been invited to her handsome classmate Don Prima's latest party, and
she has gotten a tune-up and a new paint job just for the occasion. However,
Brit and Tiff are ready to do anything to [sabotage](/wiki/Sabotage
"Sabotage") Jenny's chances to impress at the party.  
13 | 7a | "The Return of Raggedy Android" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chris Mitchell & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | September 19, 2003 (2003-09-19)  
The owner of Mezmer's, a popular hangout spot for teens all over town,
enforces a strict "No Robots" policy. Desperate to get in, Jenny dons the new
and improved exo-skin to pass off as a perfectly normal attractive human girl.
However, the exo-skin turns out to have a mind of its own and refuses to let
Jenny take it off or fight a group of alien space bikers.  
14 | 7b | "The Boy Who Cried Robot" | [Bob Jaques](/wiki/Bob_Jaques "Bob Jaques") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Mary Hanley | September 19, 2003 (2003-09-19)  
Tuck keeps interrupting Jenny's daily activity for every possible favor. When
a big problem arises, however, Tuck's call for help winds up going ignored.  
15 | 8a | "Sibling Tsunami" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Mary Hanley | October 13, 2003 (2003-10-13)  
When Jenny finds and reactivates her "sisters"–early XJ prototypes 1 through
8–she is beyond happy. Each sister has her own personality, however, and they
do not all have the same level of friendliness that Jenny has.  
16 | 8b | "I Was A Preschool Dropout" | Randy Myers & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | October 13, 2003 (2003-10-13)  
Having been found to have only been activated for five years, the school
system declares that Jenny has to be moved into a grade level that
correspondes her "age". Jenny finds herself being forced to adapt to
kindergarten.  
17 | 9a | "Hostile Makeover" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Mary Hanley | October 24, 2003 (2003-10-24)  
When Jenny starts to develop face-bolts, voice changes, and excess wires
growing out of her body, Brad chalks it up to puberty. However, it soon
becomes apparent that the "puberty" is actually the doing of Queen Vexus of
the Cluster, who has infected Jenny with a virus to warp her into a loyal,
Cluster-controlled monster.  
18 | 9b | "Grid Iron Glory" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | [Trevor Wall](/wiki/Trevor_Wall "Trevor Wall") | October 24, 2003 (2003-10-24)  
Jenny becomes the star football player of the high school football team. At a
championship game, she soon finds herself facing the former Tremorton High
quarterback whom she replaced.  
19 | 10a | "Dressed To Kill" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | November 7, 2003 (2003-11-07)  
Thanks to a screw-up from one of his Cluster troops, Commander Smytus loses a
cache of super-powered Pip Crystals to the Crust Cousins. The cousins decide
to flaunt both their style and newfound powers in front of Jenny, and she must
use her keen fashion sense to save herself in time.  
20 | 10b | "Shell Game" | John Fountain & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain | November 7, 2003 (2003-11-07)  
Looking to prove to Jenny that boy robots are jerks compared to him, Sheldon
creates a mechanical suit and dubs himself the "Silver Shell". The plan
backfires, however, when Jenny starts falling for Silver Shell.  
21 | 11a | "Daydream Believer" | John Fountain & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Stephen Sandoval & Chris Mitchell | January 16, 2004 (2004-01-16)  
As a robot, Jenny wants to experience what it is like to dream. When Dr.
Wakeman installs a dream chip, Jenny's joy causes her to abuse its function
and she finds herself stuck in dream mode and sleepwalking, causing mayhem in
the process.  
22 | 11b | "This Time With Feeling" | [Robert Alvarez](/wiki/Robert_Alvarez "Robert Alvarez") & Rob Renzetti | Carlos Ramos | January 16, 2004 (2004-01-16)  
Jenny's desire to know the feeling of physical contact leads her to steal a
set of artificial nerves from Dr. Wakeman. The nerves, however, have only two
settings: tickle and pain. Jenny must manage these while fighting Himcules, a
villain whose strength increases when he sees others in pain and diminishes at
the sound of laughter.  
23 | 12a | "Saved By The Shell" | [Ron Hogart](/wiki/Ron_Hughart "Ron Hughart") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | January 23, 2004 (2004-01-23)  
Sheldon sets Jenny up for a date with Silver Shell, in hopes that he can
reveal himself to her. However, she already has a date with Don Prima, much to
Sheldon's chagrin. An evil mutant fly that can eat metal attacks people in the
restaurant while the date takes place, while Silver Shell tries to sabotage
the date by ruining Don's beautiful shoes.  
24 | 12b | "Tradeshow Showdown" | [Ron Hogart](/wiki/Ron_Hughart "Ron Hughart") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Bernie Petterson | January 23, 2004 (2004-01-23)  
Jenny is stuck going to a robot convention with Dr. Wakeman. Snubbed by all
the other robots and insulted by Dr. Wakeman's rival, Dr. Phineas Mogg, Jenny
finds herself going to a robot called Vee for comfort. However, "Vee" is
actually Vexus in disguise, seeking to recruit new Cluster members.  
25 | 13a | "The Wonderful World of Wizzly" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chris Dent | February 27, 2004 (2004-02-27)  
Jenny gets a chance to visit the theme park Wizzly World with Brad and Tuck,
and she cannot help but think that the robots in the park feel miserable. When
Jenny breaks them out of the park, however, chaos ensues.  
26 | 13b | "Call Hating" | [Tim Walker](/wiki/Tim_Walker "Tim Walker") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Ed Baker | February 27, 2004 (2004-02-27)  
When Jenny hangs up on Dr. Wakeman one too many times, the doctor desperately
reprograms Jenny's communicator to make Jenny unable to turn it off.  
  
### Season 2
(2004–05)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_My_Life_as_a_Teenage_Robot_episodes&action=edit&section=4
"Edit section: Season 2 \(2004–05\)")]

_My Life as a Teenage Robot_ season 2 episodes No. In Series | No. In Season | Title | Directed By | Storyboard By | Original Air date[4]  
---|---|---|---|---|---  
27 | 1 | "A Robot For All Seasons" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain & Brandon Kruse | December 8, 2004 (2004-12-08)  
Jenny is unwittingly programmed for evil against her will by a spoiled child
named Todd Sweeney, who uses her to ruin the holidays for all of Tremorton.
When she returns to normal, she discovers that the entire town has turned
against her, and nobody believes her pleas of innocence, except for the one
person that worships her like a goddess - Sheldon. Todd, however, still
intends to use her to ruin the year's biggest holiday—Christmas.  
28 | 2a | "Future Shock" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | January 17, 2005 (2005-01-17)  
When Tuck takes a look into Dr. Wakeman's "Future Scope" and sees a vision
which leads him to believe that Jenny will kill Brad, he takes all costs to
stop Brad from leaving for a drive-in movie showing.  
29 | 2b | "Humiliation 101" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Bernie Petterson | January 18, 2005 (2005-01-18)  
Dr. Wakeman is coming to Tremorton High to speak at a special science assembly
about Jenny. Fearing humiliation, Jenny tries to prevent her mother from
talking at the assembly.  
30 | 3a | "Last Action Zero" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain | January 18, 2005 (2005-01-18)  
Brad gets a chance to join the Skyway Patrol in hopes that he can help Jenny
in her duties. However, he soon finds himself stuck with nothing but paperwork
and paper cuts at his new job.  
31 | 3b | "Mind Over Matter" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | January 19, 2005 (2005-01-19)  
After being lectured about [planned obsolescence](/wiki/Planned_obsolescence
"Planned obsolescence") by Brad, and later finding herself unable to defeat
the energy vampire Gigawatt, Jenny fears being rendered an obsolete robot.
Determined to beat Gigawatt, she soon tries to "upgrade" herself to make up
for her weaknesses against Gigawatt.  
32 | 4a | "Love 'Em Or Leash 'Em" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Gabe Swarr | January 19, 2005 (2005-01-19)  
Jenny's new boyfriend, a male robot named Kenny built by Dr. Wakeman's rival
Dr. Mogg (who copies many of Dr. Wakeman's inventions while adding distinctive
twists), seems to be the perfect match for her at first; however, Kenny soon
starts to display oddly dog-like characteristics. Meanwhile, the new couple
attracts Sheldon's jealousy.  
33 | 4b | "Teen Team Time" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Kelly Armstrong | January 19, 2005 (2005-01-19)  
The Teen Team has come to Earth, and they are quite impressed with Jenny's
abilities. Jenny seems more than excited to join, but finds herself ignoring
her other friends in favor of a group of heroes that are mostly prejudiced
against "normal people".  
34 | 5a | "Pajama Party Prankapalooza" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Heather Martinez | January 20, 2005 (2005-01-20)  
Jenny has managed to get herself invited to Brit and Tiff's slumber party,
and, as usual, Jenny's naiveness leads her to cause mischief all over town to
impress the Crusts. Dr. Wakeman must stop Jenny before Skyway Patrol can catch
up to her daughter.  
35 | 5b | "Sister Sledgehammer" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Mike Kunkel | January 20, 2005 (2005-01-20)  
Commander Smytus has actually succeeded in assimilating Jenny into the
Cluster, and has turned her into a massive metal monster. Having been awakened
due to Jenny being in crisis, the rest of the XJ line have come to save their
captive sister.  
36 | 6a | "Dancing With My Shell" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain | April 2, 2005 (2005-04-02)  
Jenny takes the Silver Shell to the Sadie Hawkins school dance, and Sheldon
hopes that he can impress Jenny enough to reveal his identity to her.
Everything starts going wrong, however, when Letta and the Space Bikers crash
the dance.  
37 | 6b | "Around The World In Eighty Pieces" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Bernie Petterson | April 2, 2005 (2005-04-02)  
Crackerjack Cluster inventor Krackus has managed to scatter Jenny's parts all
over the world, and Brad, Tuck, and Sheldon must put their friend back
together before Krackus can call Vexus on his success.  
38 | 7a | "Armagedroid" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Tom King | March 25, 2005 (2005-03-25)  
Armagedroid—once a powerful global protector programmed to disarm and destroy
all weapons before he went rogue—returns to Tremorton, and Jenny finds herself
unable to stop such a huge robot.  
39 | 7b | "Killgore" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | [Dave Thomas](/wiki/Dave_Thomas_\(actor\) "Dave Thomas \(actor\)") | June 28, 2005 (2005-06-28)  
Killgore, a small wind-up robot, hopes to kidnap Jenny in hopes of impressing
the Cluster, but no one can resist his unintentionally cutesy appearance.  
40 | 8a | "A Pain In My Sidekick" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Bernie Petterson | July 16, 2005 (2005-07-16)  
Tuck admires the Silver Shell, so he manages to convince Sheldon into making
him Silver Shell's faithful sidekick, the Tin Can. Being a sidekick is not
quite what he expects, though.  
41 | 8b | "Crash Pad Crash" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Heather Martinez | July 23, 2005 (2005-07-23)  
Jenny's new "bachelor pad" is the new hot spot in town, but her new party
lifestyle begins to interfere with her own personal duties.  
42~43 | 9~10 | "[Escape From Cluster Prime](/wiki/Escape_from_Cluster_Prime "Escape from Cluster Prime")" | [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") & [Chris Savino](/wiki/Chris_Savino "Chris Savino") | Brandon Kruse, Heather Martinez, [Chris Reccardi](/wiki/Chris_Reccardi "Chris Reccardi") & [Bryan Andrews](/wiki/Bryan_Andrews_\(storyboard_artist\) "Bryan Andrews \(storyboard artist\)") | August 12, 2005 (2005-08-12)  
Scorned by Tremorton after ruining the town's 300th anniversary celebrations
during a fight with Vexus, Jenny gets fed up with being unappreciated by
humans and soon finds herself in Cluster Prime, the capital of Vexus' empire.
She finally gets a chance to live with other robots like her, but soon
discovers there's more to Cluster Prime than meets the eye.  
44 | 11 | "Victim of Fashion" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Alex Kirwan & Brandon Kruse | October 7, 2005 (2005-10-07)  
Not to be outdone by each other, a fashion war erupts between Jenny and the
Crust cousins. Brit and Tiff employ psychological warfare by making Jenny feel
self-conscious about her weight, so she urges Sheldon to make her as light as
possible, which results in giving up her weapons and armor.  
45 | 12a | "Designing Women" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | September 6, 2005 (2005-09-06)  
Looking to find a way into Jenny's heart, Sheldon steals a set of XJ-9
schematics from Dr. Wakeman. Vexus, however, also has eyes for the schematics,
and is willing to disguise herself as "QT2" to trick Sheldon into giving them
to her.  
46 | 12b | "Robot Riot" | John Fountain & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain | September 6, 2005 (2005-09-06)  
Jenny gives in to Tuck's request to be his entry for the hit robot combat
competition "Robot Wars", despite finding the event barbaric.  
47 | 13a | "Bradventure" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | John Fountain | September 7, 2005 (2005-09-07)  
Tired of being stuck under Jenny's shadow, Brad sets out to be his own hero.
However, he finds himself in hot water when he runs afoul of the scientist Dr.
Locus and his daughter Melody. Locus wants the XJ-9 schematics for reasons yet
unknown and when Jenny gets knocked out in battle, Brad has to prove himself.  
48 | 13b | "Mama Drama" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Heather Martinez | September 7, 2005 (2005-09-07)  
Jenny is convinced that Dr. Wakeman's new boyfriend is a psychopath.  
49 | 14a | "Toying with Jenny" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Brandon Kruse | September 9, 2005 (2005-09-09)  
The brand-new "Action Jenny" toys are a huge success, and Jenny finds herself
taken in by the fame. However, they soon turn out to be Vexus and Krackus'
newest plan to conquer the world.  
50 | 14b | "Teenage Mutant Ninja Troubles" | [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Chris Dent & John Fountain | September 9, 2005 (2005-09-09)  
Due to internal disputes, the Teen Team has broken up. With no place left to
go, Misty heads back to Earth to be with Jenny. Teased at school by the Crust
cousins for her appearance, Misty convinces Jenny to get back at them through
a prank war.  
  
### Season 3
(2008–09)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_My_Life_as_a_Teenage_Robot_episodes&action=edit&section=5
"Edit section: Season 3 \(2008–09\)")]

_My Life as a Teenage Robot_ season 3 episodes No. In Series | No. In Season | Title | Directed By | Storyboard By | Original Air date[4]  
---|---|---|---|---|---  
51 | 1a | "Weapons of Mass Distraction" | [Chris Savino](/wiki/Chris_Savino "Chris Savino"), [Chris Sauve](/wiki/Chris_Sauve "Chris Sauve") & [Rob Renzetti](/wiki/Rob_Renzetti "Rob Renzetti") | Heather Martinez | October 4, 2008 (2008-10-04)[nb 1]  
Jenny has a crush on a new kid named Travis, but there's only one problem:
Travis is afraid of anything mechanical. The scene with Travis' father in the
factory is based on the Charlie Chaplin motion picture, "Modern Times".  
52 | 1b | "There's No Place Like Home School" | Ray Pointer, Bob Nesler & Greg Miller | Bernie Petterson | October 4, 2008 (2008-10-04)[nb 1]  
Jenny winds up getting homeschooled by Dr. Wakeman due to a mishap at school
involving a student and a trashcan. Jenny may not like it, but her mother
enjoys the chance to teach her daughter... perhaps too much.
